{"question": "What action should an organization take to ensure access to shared resources is only granted to the accounts that are intended?",
"answer_choices": [
    {"answer": "Use the default IAM trust policy when granting third-party cross-account access","is_correct": "False","explanation": "Using the default IAM trust policy when granting third-party cross-account access is an anti-pattern and should be avoided. The organization should use AWS Resource Access Manager (RAM) to share resources between accounts."},
    {"answer": "Integrate access controls with operator and application lifecycle and the centralized federation provider","is_correct": "True","explanation": "Integrating access controls with operator and application lifecycle and the centralized federation provider is the best practice for managing access to shared resources across multiple accounts. The organization should use AWS RAM to share resources between accounts."},
    {"answer": "Put measures in place to protect against unintended access","is_correct": "False","explanation": "Put measures in place should be done as part of the process for managing access to shared resources, but it is not sufficient on its own. The organization should use AWS RAM to share resources between accounts."},
    {"answer": "Create an IAM cross-account role with only the privileges needed by the third party","is_correct": "False","explanation": "Creating an IAM cross-account role with only the privileges needed by the third party is part of the process for granting third-party cross-account access, but it is not sufficient on its own. The organization should use AWS RAM to share resources between accounts."}
]}

