{"question": "What is the best practice for minimizing the risk of privilege escalation when managing IAM users and roles?", 
"answer_choices": [
    {"answer": "Grant users administrator permissions","is_correct": "False","explanation": "Defaulting to granting users administrator permissions is an anti-pattern and not best practice. "},
    {"answer": "Use the root account for day-to-day activities","is_correct": "False","explanation": "The credentials for the root user should be tightly controlled and only be used for a few specific tasks. "},
    {"answer": "Delegate permission management to developers by using IAM permissions boundaries","is_correct": "True","explanation": "Using IAM permissions boundaries, you can limit the maximum permissions that developers can grant. This helps ensure that you are adhering to the principle of least privilege. "},
    {"answer": "Write least privilege IAM policies","is_correct": "False","explanation": "Least privilege IAM policies help ensure that identities are only permitted to perform the most minimal set of functions necessary to fulfill their task, while balancing usability and efficiency. However, they are not the best practice for minimizing risk of privilege escalation. "}
]}

