{"question": "What is the best practice for backing up critical data sources in the financial services company scenario described above?",
"answer_choices": [
    {"answer": "Use AWS Backup to back up data to Amazon S3 buckets and use Amazon S3 Glacier or S3 Glacier Deep Archive to reduce cost of data storage.","is_correct": "True","explanation": "AWS Backup is a tool that gives you the ability to centralize and automate data protection across AWS services. Amazon S3 can be used as a backup destination for self-managed and AWS-managed data sources. It offers multiple storage tiers such as Amazon S3 Glacier or S3 Glacier Deep Archive to reduce cost of data storage."},
    {"answer": "Use Amazon EMR to store data on HDFS and back up the data store to AWS.","is_correct": "False","explanation": "In cases where sources like Amazon EMR can be used to meet your Recovery Point Objective (RPO) and Recovery Time Objective (RTO), you might not require a backup if you can reproduce the data into EMR from S3."},
    {"answer": "Back up all data sources to AWS using AWS Storage Gateway or AWS DataSync.","is_correct": "False","explanation": "On-premises data can be backed up to the AWS Cloud using AWS Storage Gateway or AWS DataSync. Amazon S3 buckets can be used to store this data on AWS. However, only critical data sources should be backed up as some data might be able to be reproduced from other sources."},
    {"answer": "Take manual backups of data sources at a frequency that meets the Recovery Point Objective (RPO) for the workload.","is_correct": "False","explanation": "Most AWS services provides capabilities to back up workload data. AWS Backup is a managed service that enables creating backups of various data sources on AWS. These services also have native capabilities to create backups. Establish a cadence for backing up data that meets the Recovery Point Objective (RPO) for the workload."}
]}

